2022 annual CDC survey data of 400k+ adults related to their health status What subject does the dataset cover? According to the CDC, heart disease is a leading cause of death for people of most races in the U.S. (African Americans, American Indians and Alaska Natives, and whites). About half of all Americans (47%) have at least 1 of 3 major risk factors for heart disease: high blood pressure, high cholesterol, and smoking. Other key indicators include diabetes status, obesity (high BMI), not getting enough physical activity, or drinking too much alcohol. Identifying and preventing the factors that have the greatest impact on heart disease is very important in healthcare.

Where did the data set come from and what treatments has it undergone? The dataset originally comes from the CDC and is a major part of the Behavioral Risk Factor Surveillance System (BRFSS), which conducts annual telephone surveys to collect data on the health status of U.S. residents. As described by the CDC: âEstablished in 1984 with 15 states, BRFSS now collects data in all 50 states, the District of Columbia, and three U.S. territories. BRFSS completes more than 400,000 adult interviews each year, making it the largest continuously conducted health survey system in the world. The most recent dataset includes data from 2023.

The code below includes the functions that were used to plot the checkups against race. There are three functions: one without separate those who had and hadnât suffered a heart attack, one for those who had suffered a heart attack, and one for those who hadnât suffered a heart attack. The code plots them as a stacked bar graph with percentages that represent how much each portion takes up of the bar labeled on it. The are ordered from most to least recent in terms of checkup time from bottom to top.

# No heart attack
def plot_stacked_checkup_by_race_no(sliced_df):
    filtered_df = sliced_df[sliced_df['HadHeartAttack'] == 'No']

    grouped = filtered_df.groupby(['RaceEthnicityCategory', 'LastCheckupTime']).size().unstack(fill_value=0)

    percentages = grouped.div(grouped.sum(axis=1), axis=0) * 100

    checkup_order = ['< 1 year', '1-2 years', '2-5 years', '> 5 years']

    percentages = percentages[checkup_order]

    ax = percentages.plot(kind='bar', stacked=True, figsize=(10, 6))

    plt.xlabel('Race/Ethnicity')
    plt.ylabel('Percentage')
    plt.title('No Heart Attack: Last Checkup Times within each Race/Ethnicity')
    plt.legend(title='Last Checkup Time', loc='lower right')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)

    for rect in ax.patches:
        width, height = rect.get_width(), rect.get_height()
        x, y = rect.get_x(), rect.get_y()
        if height > 1:
            label_text = f'{height:.1f}%'
            ax.text(x + width / 2, y + height / 2, label_text, ha='center', va='center')

    plt.show()

# Yes heart attack
def plot_stacked_checkup_by_race_yes(sliced_df):
    
    filtered_df = sliced_df[sliced_df['HadHeartAttack'] == 'Yes']

    grouped = filtered_df.groupby(['RaceEthnicityCategory', 'LastCheckupTime']).size().unstack(fill_value=0)

    percentages = grouped.div(grouped.sum(axis=1), axis=0) * 100

    checkup_order = ['< 1 year', '1-2 years', '2-5 years', '> 5 years']

    percentages = percentages[checkup_order]

    ax = percentages.plot(kind='bar', stacked=True, figsize=(10, 6))

    plt.xlabel('Race/Ethnicity')
    plt.ylabel('Percentage')
    plt.title('Yes Heart Attack: Last Checkup Times within each Race/Ethnicity')
    plt.legend(title='Last Checkup Time', loc='lower right')

2.3.2 Sleep

Letâs first look at the variable SleepHours as it is our only continuous variable in the lifestyle_choices_cleaned dataframe:

# Select relevant columns
sleep_and_heart_attack_cleaned = lifestyle_choices_cleaned[['SleepHours', 'HadHeartAttack']]

# Descriptive Statistics
print("Descriptive Statistics:\n", sleep_and_heart_attack_cleaned.groupby('HadHeartAttack')['SleepHours'].describe())

# Visualization - Box Plot
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.boxplot(x='HadHeartAttack', y='SleepHours', data=sleep_and_heart_attack_cleaned, palette='viridis')

# Statistical Test - t-test
from scipy.stats import ttest_ind

had_heart_attack = sleep_and_heart_attack_cleaned[sleep_and_heart_attack_cleaned['HadHeartAttack'] == 'Yes']['SleepHours']
no_heart_attack = sleep_and_heart_attack_cleaned[sleep_and_heart_attack_cleaned['HadHeartAttack'] == 'No']['SleepHours']

t_stat, p_value = ttest_ind(had_heart_attack, no_heart_attack)

print(f"T-statistic: {t_stat}")
print(f"P-value: {p_value}")

# Interpretation of the t-test
alpha = 0.05
if p_value < alpha:
    print("Reject the null hypothesis: There is a significant difference in sleep hours between those who had a heart attack and those who did not.")
else:
    print("Fail to reject the null hypothesis: There is no significant difference in sleep hours between those who had a heart attack and those who did not.")

Reject the null hypothesis: There is a significant difference in sleep hours between those who had a heart attack and those who did not.

Result:

  • The t-test indicates a statistically significant difference in mean sleep hours between individuals who had a heart attack and those who did not.

  • However, itâs important to note that while the difference is statistically significant, the practical significance may be limited given the small difference in means (0.03 hours) and the large sample size.

  • This could be due to older people, who are more likely to have heart attacks, also sleeping more, confounding the SleepHours variable

  • This could also be due to people who had heart attacks beginning to sleep more.

2.3.3 Categorical Variables

Now letâs look at the rest of our variables:

# Select relevant categorical columns
categorical_variables = ['PhysicalActivities', 'SmokerStatus', 'ECigaretteUsage', 'AlcoholDrinkers']

# Create subplots
fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=len(categorical_variables), ncols=1, figsize=(8, 2 * len(categorical_variables)))

# Iterate through categorical variables
for i, variable in enumerate(categorical_variables):
    
    # Descriptive Statistics
    print(f"Descriptive Statistics for {variable}:\n", lifestyle_choices_cleaned.groupby(['HadHeartAttack', variable]).size())
    
    # Statistical Test - Chi-Square Test
    contingency_table = pd.crosstab(lifestyle_choices_cleaned['HadHeartAttack'], lifestyle_choices_cleaned[variable])
    chi2_stat, p_value, _, _ = chi2_contingency(contingency_table)
    
    print(f"\nChi-Square Test for Independence between HadHeartAttack and {variable}:")
    print(f"Chi-Square Statistic: {chi2_stat}")
    print(f"P-value: {p_value}")
    
    if p_value < alpha:
        print(f"Reject the null hypothesis: There is a significant association between HadHeartAttack and {variable}.")
    else:
        print(f"Fail to reject the null hypothesis: There is no significant association between HadHeartAttack and {variable}.")
        
    print("\n" + "="*50 + "\n")  # Add a separator for better readability
    
    # Visualization - Proportion Plot
    proportions = contingency_table.div(contingency_table.sum(axis=1), axis=0)
    ax = proportions.plot(kind='bar', stacked=True, ax=axes[i], colormap='viridis')
    ax.legend(loc='center left', bbox_to_anchor=(1, 0.5))  # Move the legend to the right side
    axes[i].set_title(f'Proportion of {variable} by HadHeartAttack')
    axes[i].set_xlabel('HadHeartAttack')
    axes[i].set_ylabel('Proportion')

# Adjust layout
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Function to calculate CramÃ©r's V
def cramers_v(confusion_matrix):
    chi2 = chi2_contingency(confusion_matrix)[0]
    n = confusion_matrix.sum().sum()
    phi2 = chi2 / n
    r, k = confusion_matrix.shape
    phi2corr = max(0, phi2 - ((k - 1) * (r - 1)) / (n - 1))
    rcorr = r - ((r - 1) ** 2) / (n - 1)
    kcorr = k - ((k - 1) ** 2) / (n - 1)
    return np.sqrt(phi2corr / min((kcorr - 1), (rcorr - 1)))

# Calculate CramÃ©r's V for each variable
for variable in categorical_variables:
    contingency_table = pd.crosstab(lifestyle_choices_cleaned['HadHeartAttack'], lifestyle_choices_cleaned[variable])
    cramers_value = cramers_v(contingency_table)
    
    print(f"CramÃ©r's V for {variable}: {cramers_value}")

for age_category in age_category_order:
    # Select data for the current age category
    current_age_category_data = merged_data_subset[merged_data_subset['AgeCategory'] == age_category]

    # Extract SleepHours for 'Yes' and 'No' HadHeartAttack
    had_heart_attack = current_age_category_data[current_age_category_data['HadHeartAttack'] == 'Yes']['SleepHours']
    no_heart_attack = current_age_category_data[current_age_category_data['HadHeartAttack'] == 'No']['SleepHours']

        print("Fail to reject the null hypothesis: There is no significant difference in sleep hours between those who had a heart attack and those who did not.")

# Function to create barplots for each category
def create_barplots(category_df, title_prefix):
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=2, ncols=2, figsize=(12, 10))

    for i, category in enumerate(category_df.iloc[:, :4].columns):
        contingency_table = pd.crosstab(category_df[category], category_df['AlcoholDrinkers_Yes'])
        proportions = contingency_table.div(contingency_table.sum(axis=1), axis=0)
        proportions.index = proportions.index.map({0: 'No', 1: 'Yes'})  # Replace 0 and 1 labels
        ax = proportions.plot(kind='bar', stacked=True, colormap='viridis', ax=axes[i // 2, i % 2])
        ax.legend(['False', 'True'], loc='center left', bbox_to_anchor=(1, 0.5))
        ax.set_title(f'{title_prefix} {category} by Alcohol Consumption')
        ax.set_xlabel('Alcohol Drinkers')
        ax.set_xticklabels(ax.get_xticklabels(), rotation=0)
        ax.set_ylabel('Proportion')

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

ax = proportions_yes.plot(kind='bar', stacked=True, colormap='viridis', figsize=(10, 6))
ax.legend(['Not a drinker', 'Drinker'], loc='center left', bbox_to_anchor=(1, 0.5))
ax.set_title('Proportion of AlcoholDrinkers by HadHeartAttack (PhysicalActivities == Yes)')
ax.set_xlabel('HadHeartAttack')
ax.set_xticklabels(ax.get_xticklabels(), rotation=0)
ax.set_ylabel('Proportion')

# Perform chi-squared test for yes PhysicalActivities
chi2_stat_yes, p_value_yes, _, _ = chi2_contingency(contingency_table['Yes'])
ax.text(0, -0.25, f'Chi-Square p-value: {p_value_yes:.4f}', transform=ax.transAxes)

# Show the plot
plt.show()

Result:

  • The p-values are less than 0.05 for both (PhysicalActivities == Yes) and (PhysicalActivities == No), meaning that drinking alcohol still has a positive correlation with not having a heart attack.

def get_region(x):
    west = ['WA', 'OR', 'CA', 'NV', 'ID', 'UT', 'MT', 'WY', 'CO', 'AK', 'HI']
    southwest = ['AZ', 'NM', 'TX', 'OK']
    midwest = ['ND', 'SD', 'NE', 'KS', 'MN', 'IA', 'MO', 'WI', 'IL', 'MI', 'IN', 'OH']
    southeast = ['AR', 'LA', 'MS', 'AL', 'TN', 'KY', 'WV', 'VA', 'NC', 'SC', 'GA', 'FL']
    northeast = ['ME', 'NH', 'VT', 'MA', 'RI', 'CT', 'NY', 'NJ', 'PA', 'DE', 'MD', 'DC']
    
    if x["State"] in west:
        return 'West'
    elif x["State"] in southwest:
        return 'Southwest'
    elif x["State"] in midwest:
        return 'Midwest'
    elif x["State"] in southeast:
        return 'Southeast'
    elif x["State"] in northeast:
        return 'Northeast'
